# Cloud Computing Lab - Program 3
## Program 3: Demonstrate Load Balancer and Elastic IP Concept in AWS

# Step-by-Step Execution

---

## Step 1: Verify Existing VPC Resources

Since VPC, Internet Gateway, Route Table, Public Subnet, Security Group, and Key Pair were already created in Program 1, we first verified them.

Go to:

AWS Console → VPC Dashboard

Check the following resources:

VPC: Lab-VPC
CIDR: 10.1.0.0/16

Internet Gateway: Lab-IGW

Route Table: Public-RT

Public Subnet: Public-Subnet
CIDR: 10.1.1.0/24

The route table should already contain:

10.1.0.0/16  → local
0.0.0.0/0    → Lab-IGW

This route allows internet access for resources launched inside the public subnet.

Step 2: Create Second Public Subnet

An Application Load Balancer requires at least two public subnets in different Availability Zones.

Go to:

VPC Dashboard → Subnets

Click:

Create subnet

Select the existing VPC:

VPC: Lab-VPC

Enter subnet details:

Subnet name: Public-Subnet-2
Availability Zone: ap-south-1b
IPv4 subnet CIDR block: 10.1.2.0/24

Click:

Create subnet
Step 3: Enable Auto-Assign Public IPv4 for Second Subnet

Go to:

VPC Dashboard → Subnets

Select:

Public-Subnet-2

Click:

Actions → Edit subnet settings

Enable:

Auto-assign public IPv4 address

Click:

Save

This ensures that EC2 instances launched in this subnet receive a public IPv4 address automatically.

Step 4: Associate Second Subnet with Existing Public Route Table

Go to:

VPC Dashboard → Route Tables

Select the existing route table:

Public-RT

Go to:

Subnet associations

Click:

Edit subnet associations

Select both public subnets:

Public-Subnet
Public-Subnet-2

Click:

Save associations

Now both subnets are public because both are associated with the route table having:

0.0.0.0/0 → Lab-IGW
Step 5: Update Security Group

Go to:

EC2 Dashboard → Security Groups

Open the existing security group:

Lab-SG

Edit inbound rules and make sure the following rules are present:

Type: SSH
Protocol: TCP
Port: 22
Source: My IP or 0.0.0.0/0
Type: HTTP
Protocol: TCP
Port: 80
Source: 0.0.0.0/0

For lab exam execution, using 0.0.0.0/0 makes testing easier.

HTTP port 80 is required because the load balancer will forward browser requests to Apache running on EC2 instances.

Step 6: Launch First Ubuntu EC2 Instance

Go to:

EC2 Dashboard → Instances

Click:

Launch instances

Enter instance name:

PG03-Server-1

Select AMI:

Ubuntu Server

Select instance type:

t2.micro

or

t3.micro

Select key pair:

cloud-lab-key

In Network settings, click:

Edit

Select:

VPC: Lab-VPC
Subnet: Public-Subnet
Auto-assign public IP: Enable
Firewall: Select existing security group
Security Group: Lab-SG

Now open:

Advanced details → User data

Paste the following script:

#!/bin/bash
sudo apt update -y
sudo apt install -y apache2
HOSTNAME=$(hostname)
PRIVATE_IP=$(hostname -I | awk '{print $1}')
echo "<html>
<head>
<title>PG-03 Server 1</title>
</head>
<body>
<h1>PG-03: Application Load Balancer Demo</h1>
<h2>This response is from Server 1</h2>
<p><strong>Hostname:</strong> $HOSTNAME</p>
<p><strong>Private IP:</strong> $PRIVATE_IP</p>
</body>
</html>" | sudo tee /var/www/html/index.html
sudo systemctl start apache2
sudo systemctl enable apache2

Click:

Launch instance
