Step 8: Test Apache Web Server on Both Instances

Copy the public IPv4 address of:

PG03-Server-1

Open it in browser:

http://SERVER-1-PUBLIC-IP

Expected output:

PG-03: Application Load Balancer Demo
This response is from Server 1
Hostname: ...
Private IP: ...

Now copy the public IPv4 address of:

PG03-Server-2

Open it in browser:

http://SERVER-2-PUBLIC-IP

Expected output:

PG-03: Application Load Balancer Demo
This response is from Server 2
Hostname: ...
Private IP: ...

If both pages open successfully, Apache is running correctly on both EC2 instances.

Step 9: Create Target Group

Go to:

EC2 Dashboard → Target Groups

Click:

Create target group

Select target type:

Instances

Enter the following details:

Target group name: pg03-target-group
Protocol: HTTP
Port: 80
VPC: Lab-VPC
Protocol version: HTTP1

Health check settings:

Health check protocol: HTTP
Health check path: /

Click:

Next

Select both instances:

PG03-Server-1
PG03-Server-2

Click:

Include as pending below

Then click:

Create target group
Step 10: Check Target Health

Open:

EC2 Dashboard → Target Groups → pg03-target-group → Targets

Wait until both instances show:

Healthy

If targets are unhealthy, wait for 1–2 minutes and refresh.

If they are still unhealthy, check:

Apache is running on both instances
Security group allows HTTP port 80
Instances are running
Target group health check path is /
Instances are added to target group
Step 11: Create Application Load Balancer

Go to:

EC2 Dashboard → Load Balancers

Click:

Create load balancer

Choose:

Application Load Balancer

Click:

Create

Enter basic configuration:

Load balancer name: pg03-alb
Scheme: Internet-facing
IP address type: IPv4

In network mapping, select:

VPC: Lab-VPC

Select both Availability Zones and public subnets:

ap-south-1a → Public-Subnet
ap-south-1b → Public-Subnet-2

In security group section, select:

Lab-SG

In listeners and routing, enter:

Protocol: HTTP
Port: 80
Forward to: pg03-target-group

Click:

Create load balancer
Step 12: Access Application Load Balancer DNS

Go to:

EC2 Dashboard → Load Balancers

Select:

pg03-alb

Copy the DNS name of the load balancer.

It will look similar to:

pg03-alb-123456789.ap-south-1.elb.amazonaws.com

Open in browser:

http://LOAD-BALANCER-DNS-NAME

Example:

http://pg03-alb-123456789.ap-south-1.elb.amazonaws.com

Expected output may show:

This response is from Server 1

or:

This response is from Server 2

Refresh the browser multiple times. The response should toggle between the two EC2 instances.

Step 13: Test Load Balancer from Ubuntu Terminal

Open Ubuntu terminal and run:

curl http://LOAD-BALANCER-DNS-NAME

Run it multiple times:

curl http://LOAD-BALANCER-DNS-NAME
curl http://LOAD-BALANCER-DNS-NAME
curl http://LOAD-BALANCER-DNS-NAME

Expected output should show responses from both servers:

This response is from Server 1

and:

This response is from Server 2
